{{see also|Tibial plateau fracture}}

A '''bumper fracture''' is a [[Bone fracture|fracture]] of the [[Human anatomical terms#Anatomical directions|lateral]] [[tibia]]l plateau caused by the bumper of a car coming into contact with the outer side of the knee when a person is standing.
Specifically, it is caused by a forced [[Valgus deformity|valgus]] applied to the [[knee]]. This causes the lateral part of the distal [[femur]] and the lateral tibial plateau to come into contact, compressing the tibial plateau and causing the tibia to fracture. The name of the injury is because it was described as being caused by the impact of a [[Bumper (automobile)|car bumper]] on the lateral side of the knee while the foot is planted on the ground, although this mechanism is only seen in about 25% of tibial plateau fractures.<ref>[http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/396920-overview ''Tibial Plateau Fractures''] at [[eMedicine]]</ref>

Fracture of the neck of the [[fibula]] may also be found, and associated injury to the [[medial collateral ligament]] or [[cruciate ligament]]s occurs in about 10% of cases.<ref>{{cite journal |author=APLEY AG |title=Fractures of the lateral tibial condyle treated by skeletal traction and early mobilisation; a review of sixty cases with special reference to the long-term results |journal=J Bone Joint Surg Br |volume=38-B |issue=3 |pages=699–708 |date=August 1956 |pmid=13357593 |doi= |url=http://www.jbjs.org.uk/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=13357593 |accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Skeletal Trauma |url=https://www.med-ed.virginia.edu/courses/rad/ext/7knee/27.html |website=www.med-ed.virginia.edu |accessdate=13 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> 

== History ==
The term "bumper fracture" was coined in 1929 by Cotton and Berg.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bumper Fracture of the Knee |url=https://www.mdedge.com/ccjm/article/90841/bumper-fracture-knee |website=www.mdedge.com |accessdate=13 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

