{{Infobox organization |name=International Carnivorous Plant Society |logo=International Carnivorous Plant Society (logo).png |type=[[501(c)#501(c)(3)|501(c)(3)]] [[non-profit organization]] |founded_date= |founders= |location_city= |location_country= |origins= |key_people= |area_served=Global |focus= |method= |revenue= |endowment= |total grant commitments since 1994= |total 2012 grant payments= |num_employees= |owner= |Non-profit_slogan=Enjoying plants through cultivation... working to conserve wild habitat for the future... promoting research |former name= |homepage={{URL|http://www.carnivorousplants.org}} }}
The '''International Carnivorous Plant Society''' ('''ICPS''') is a [[non-profit organization]] founded in 1972. It is the [[International Cultivar Registration Authority]] for [[carnivorous plant]]s.<ref>[http://www.carnivorousplants.org/about/aboutmain.html About the ICPS]. International Carnivorous Plant Society.</ref> As of June 2011, the society had around 1400 members.<ref>Baldwin, M. 2011. From the president. ''[[Carnivorous Plant Newsletter]]'' '''40'''(2): 43.</ref>
The ICPS is probably best known for its quarterly publication, the ''[[Carnivorous Plant Newsletter]]''. __NOTOC__
==Conservation efforts== The ICPS has set up the ''Nepenthes clipeata'' Survival Project (NcSP) to facilitate ''ex situ'' conservation of this species.<ref name=NcSP>Cantley, R., C.M. Clarke, J. Cokendolpher, B. Rice & A. Wistuba 2004. [http://www.sarracenia.com/pubs/ncsp.doc ''Nepenthes clipeata'' Survival Project]. International Carnivorous Plant Society.</ref> With only an estimated 15 plants remaining in the wild as of 1995, ''[[Nepenthes clipeata]]'' is the most [[endangered species|endangered]] of all known tropical [[pitcher plant]]s.<ref>Simpson, R.B. 1995. ''Nepenthes'' and conservation. ''Curtis's Botanical Magazine'' '''12''': 111–118.</ref> It is estimated that there are only three or four genetically-distinct lines of "white market" (legally collected) plants in cultivation.<ref name=NcSP />
The ICPS partially funded the establishment of The Rare ''Nepenthes'' Collection, which aims to conserve four of the rarest ''Nepenthes'' species: ''[[Nepenthes aristolochioides|N.&nbsp;aristolochioides]]'', ''[[Nepenthes clipeata|N.&nbsp;clipeata]]'', ''[[Nepenthes khasiana|N.&nbsp;khasiana]]'', and ''[[Nepenthes rigidifolia|N.&nbsp;rigidifolia]]''.<ref>Ziemer, B. 2010. Exciting conservation news: The Rare ''Nepenthes'' Collection project! ''[[Carnivorous Plant Newsletter]]'' '''39'''(3): 67.</ref>
